## Tool Directory Routing

When a request needs a specialized tool family and the right tool has not
already been selected, read the `tool-index` skill first. Use it only to choose
the category, then read the selected category skill.

If the category chooses a complex tool with a tool-specific skill, read that
skill before using the tool. If the category chooses a simple helper with no
tool-specific skill, use the helper directly from the category guidance.

Trigger routing for internet research, website reading or scraping, browser
operation, agent/tool setup, local file or media handling, visual assets,
structured live data, MCP tool routing, or uncertainty about the correct tool
family.

Skip routing for primitive actions such as editing files, running known
commands, running tests, updating plans, simple shell inspection, continuing an
already selected workflow, or using a concrete tool explicitly named by the
user.

Do not force every tool call through the directory. Follow project-specific
code-discovery instructions directly.

## Tool Onboarding Gate

Use this single-skill gate when only `tool-routing-architecture` is installed.
If Claude Code has a separate `tool-onboarding` skill, change the first sentence
below to read `tool-onboarding`; that skill should delegate to the architecture
skill for A/B/C classification and layer rules.

Before installing, enabling, configuring, repairing, updating, or removing any
tool, MCP server, skill, plugin, CLI, external API integration, API-key-backed
service, PATH entry, or tool routing rule, read the tool-routing architecture
skill.

Tool setup is complete only after the capability is classified as A, B, or C and
routing is updated or explicitly left unchanged.

For A tools, install or create the Layer 2 tool-specific skill first, then wire
it into the relevant Layer 1 category. If no local Layer 2 skill exists, search
official GitHub/docs for a maintained skill. If none exists, write one from
official docs, README, CLI help, MCP schemas, examples, and auth docs.

For B helpers, add concise category guidance and state that no tool-specific
skill is required. For C primitives or defaults, leave them out of the
directory.

When removing, disabling, or replacing a tool, remove its Layer 1 routes, delete
or archive its Layer 2 skill when unused, update replacements, clean global
rules/docs/examples/config references, and search for dangling references before
declaring completion.

Do not update Layer 0 unless a new user-intent category is required. Do not
enable plugins or modify model/provider/API endpoint settings unless explicitly
asked.
